00:00:05.040 --> 00:00:08.020
it's essential to understand who will be affected

4
00:00:08.020 --> 00:00:11.070
by the changes you're introducing.

5
00:00:11.070 --> 00:00:14.020
Identifying these key areas and leaders

6
00:00:14.020 --> 00:00:17.080
can ultimately spell success or failure

7
00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:20.000
for your transformation.

8
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.040
Strictly speaking, everyone in your organization

9
00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:25.040
is a customer of IT.

10
00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:28.030
However, it's helpful to spend some time

11
00:00:28.030 --> 00:00:30.080
identifying your key customer groups

12
00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:34.090
and strategize how your transformation will affect them.

13
00:00:34.090 --> 00:00:37.050
A simple technique to use in identifying

14
00:00:37.050 --> 00:00:40.040
your key stakeholders is to look at data

15
00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:43.030
related to service and support requests.

16
00:00:43.030 --> 00:00:45.040
The goal here is to understand

17
00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:48.050
who the heaviest users of your IT services are.

18
00:00:48.050 --> 00:00:52.080
What's important is knowing their department or area

19
00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:55.080
and getting a rough count of how many requests

20
00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:58.070
or services have been provided.

21
00:00:58.070 --> 00:01:01.030
For example, let's say I'm the CIO

22
00:01:01.030 --> 00:01:04.020
of a large insurance organization.

23
00:01:04.020 --> 00:01:07.060
I've reviewed my service requests for the last two years

24
00:01:07.060 --> 00:01:09.090
and see that most of the requests

25
00:01:09.090 --> 00:01:11.090
come from the claims department,

26
00:01:11.090 --> 00:01:14.030
and the fewest from finance.

27
00:01:14.030 --> 00:01:16.070
Now that I have this data in hand,

28
00:01:16.070 --> 00:01:19.080
I'm going to layer in what I know about my projects

29
00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:22.020
over the last few years.

30
00:01:22.020 --> 00:01:25.080
In this case, I'm looking to identify the departments

31
00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:29.020
or areas that had projects with IT resources

32
00:01:29.020 --> 00:01:32.030
and the relative size of those efforts.

33
00:01:32.030 --> 00:01:34.030
Again, I see that the claims department

34
00:01:34.030 --> 00:01:37.000
has kept us very busy

